		<content type="html" xml:base="http://ceruleansanctum.com/2008/12/wordpress-27.html">&lt;p&gt;I installed WordPress 2.7 last night, probably one of the first people to do so.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So if you see any weirdness on the blog, let me know in the comments or send me an email.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This is a major upgrade of the software. Lots of promises and excitement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My thoughts:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left: 30px;"&gt;It&amp;#8217;s definitely prettier to look at on the back end.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left: 30px;"&gt;Everything I read said this version smoked speed-wise. If this is smoke, I wonder where the fire is, &amp;#8217;cause 2.7 is only fast if you think glaciers are swift. I&amp;#8217;d say it takes two minutes per page to load anything on the back end. Even Cerulean Sanctum loads slower on the front end. I&amp;#8217;ve got the page speeds to prove it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left: 30px;"&gt;The WordPress folks did extensive usability testing of their new vertically oriented back end, but they must&amp;#8217;ve tested on 1600&amp;#215;1200 portrait monitors because I was reduced to scrolling everything constantly on my old 1024&amp;#215;768-resolution setup. The new layout made the post entry text box rival a runway model in skinniness. Fortunately, I used a menu plugin to make the menus horizontal dropdowns again.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left: 30px;"&gt;You need a new template/theme to take advantage of the built-in threaded comments. I knew that, but with so few 2.7 capable themes out, this blog won&amp;#8217;t be getting a facelift for a while yet.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style="padding-left: 30px;"&gt;On the plus side, the plugins I run that didn&amp;#8217;t work with 2.7 were swiftly updated by their authors this morning, so yes, sometimes open source DOES work.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Verdict: so far, deeply disappointed. The reality isn&amp;#8217;t living up to the hype.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This feed is from Cerulean Sanctum (http://ceruleansanctum.com), a blog by Dan Edelen that covers issues facing the American Church.&lt;/p&gt;
