		<content type="html" xml:base="http://ceruleansanctum.com/2008/12/beliefnet.html">&lt;p&gt;A question for readers:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I was approached by a representative from BeliefNet, the enormous &amp;#8220;all things to all people&amp;#8221; religious site, because they want to syndicate one of my posts (&amp;#8221;&lt;a title="Link to previous post" href="http://ceruleansanctum.com/2007/01/the-worlds-best-bible-reading-program.html" target="_blank"&gt;The World&amp;#8217;s Best Bible-Reading Program&lt;/a&gt;&amp;#8220;). That post is the number one post on Cerulean Sanctum, with nearly 10,000 unique hits from all over the world in just the last 10 months. It&amp;#8217;s also the number one result in Google for the search term &amp;#8220;Bible reading program.&amp;#8221;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So I&amp;#8217;ve been struggling with whether this is a good thing. If I let them syndicate the post, I would still keep the post on my site, but they would also post it on theirs. They would include a link back to Cerulean Sanctum. I&amp;#8217;m sure that due to their size, their version of the post would eclipse Cerulean Sanctum&amp;#8217;s eventually. Whether that helps or hurts traffic here is something I can&amp;#8217;t assess without further info.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Has anyone ever had BeliefNet syndicate one of their posts? Did it help or hurt traffic?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I also have some qualms about BeliefNet in general. The &amp;#8220;all things to all people&amp;#8221; part of it troubles me. But then again, maybe I&amp;#8217;m just hypersensitive.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Anyone out there have any thoughts on this?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This feed is from Cerulean Sanctum (http://ceruleansanctum.com), a blog by Dan Edelen that covers issues facing the American Church.&lt;/p&gt;
